Exploration of Prosper Loan Dataset¶

by Farnaz Zarian¶

Project Overview¶

This project explores data from Prosper which is America's first marketplace lending platform. Prosper has funded over 12 billion dollars in loans. On porsper, borrowers list their loan requests between 2,000 and 40,000 dollars and individual investors can invest in as little as 25 dollars in their listing of choice.

Preliminary Wrangling & Exploratory Data Analysis¶

This exploration will contain statistics with visualizations to build understanding of Prosper dataset. The dataset consists of 81 variables and 113,937 observations. Visualizations will include univariate, bivariate and multivariate visualizations of several variables in the dataset, allowing the reader to gain understanding of variable distributions as well as their relationships.

What is the structure of the dataset?¶

The loan dataset consists of 113,937 rows and 81 columns. 61 of the 81 variables are numeric, most of which have no missing values.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in the dataset?¶

Borrower APR and Original Loan Amount are the main features of interest in this exploration.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

DebtToIncomeRatio, Stated Monthly Income, Cumulative service fees paid by the investors who have invested in the loan, Borrower State, Occupation, Loan Status, Loan Term and Employment Status can help support my investigation into the main features of interest.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will investigate distributions of individual variables.

In [78]:
# Look at the histogram of the Borrower APR
sb.displot(loans['BorrowerAPR'], kind = 'hist', bins=50);
plt.xlim(0.05, .45);
plt.xlabel('Borrower APR', fontsize=12);
plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=12);
The distribution of borrower APR looks multimodal. There are small peaks around 0.1, 0.13, 0.2, 0.22, 0.24, 0.29, 0.3 and 0.37 APRS. There is a sharp peak around 0.36 APR. There are very few loans with APRs more than 0.42.¶
In [72]:
# Look at the histogram of the loan original amount
bins = np.arange(0, loans['LoanOriginalAmount'].max()+ 100, 100);
sb.displot(loans['LoanOriginalAmount'], kind = 'hist', bins=100);
plt.xlim(1000, 35000);
plt.xlabel('Original Loan Amount', fontsize=12);
plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=12);

The distribution of Original Loan Amount is multimodal. Thre is an interesting pattern in Original Loan Amounts, where there is a large spike around a single value, then a sudden tailing off to the right until the next spike. That's why I set the bin size small (100) and zoomed into a narrower range of values to clearly see the spikes in the data values. Perhaps these spikes come about as part of the psychology of round numbers (Ex. 2000, 3000, 5000, 10000, 15000, 2000, 25000 and 35000)? Overal, the vast majority of loan amounts are less than 25,0000 dollars.¶

Bivariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will investigate relationships between pairs of variables in my data.

Before starting with individual bivariate plots, let's look at the pairwise relationships of our numerical variables of interest, to get an overal view on how to move forward with the exploration.¶

In [112]:
sb.pairplot(loans, vars= ['BorrowerAPR',  'EstimatedReturn', 'LoanOriginalAmount',
                          'StatedMonthlyIncome']);

Pairplot shows that there is a positive correlation between borrower APR and estimated return. Also, There looks to be a negative correlation between borrower APR and original loan amount. Let's investigate these correlations further.¶

In [394]:
numerical_vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'LoanOriginalAmount',  'StatedMonthlyIncome',
                  'EstimatedReturn']
# Correlation Matrices 
plt.figure(figsize = [15, 10])
grid_kws = {"height_ratios": (.5, .5), "hspace": .1}
sb.heatmap(loans[numerical_vars].corr(), annot = True, fmt = '.2f',
           cmap = 'vlag_r', center = 0, cbar_kws = {'orientation': 'horizontal'});
plt.title('Heatmap of Numerical Variables', fontsize=14, y=1.05);

As seen from the heatmap above, we can see a strong positive correlation between Borrower APR and Estimated Return with correlation coefficient of 0.79. Also, Borrower APR looks to have a negative relationship with the original loan amount. However, Borrower APR does not seem to be highly correlated with the Stated Monthly Income of the borrower. Let's look into these relationships further in the plots below as the above correlations are computed based on strength of linear relationship in the correlation matrices.¶

In [182]:
# Sample 5,000 loans to make the plots readable and less busy
loans_sample = loans.sample(5000)
g = sb.PairGrid(data = loans_sample, vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'LoanOriginalAmount',
                                             'StatedMonthlyIncome', 'EstimatedReturn'])
g = g.map_diag(plt.hist)
g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter, alpha = 0.05);

Looking at the correlation matrix, we can see that the correlation coefficient between the borrower APR and original loan amount is -0.32. We can also see the negative correlation between these two variables from the scatter plot above.¶

As seen from both the correlation matrices and the scatter plots, borrower APR has a strong positive correlation with the estimated return. The interesting relationships are the relationships between the stated monthly income with the borrower APR and the original loan amount. it looks like a correlation does not exist (correlation coefficient of -0.08 or 0.2 and the corresponding flat lines in the scatter plots). Let's dig deeper into this.¶

In [387]:
categorical_vars = ['ProsperScore', 'Term', 'EmploymentStatus', 'IncomeRange']

# Plot numeric variables against categorical variables
plt.figure(figsize = [30, 30]);
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0];
g = sb.PairGrid(data = loans, x_vars = categorical_vars,
                y_vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'LoanOriginalAmount'], despine=False);
g.map(sb.violinplot, inner = 'box', height=3, aspect=.8, saturation=0.75);
g.fig.set_size_inches(20,10);
for ax in g.axes.flat: 
    ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), size = 12, rotation=45);
g.fig.suptitle('Violin Plots of Categorical Variables', fontsize=18, y=1.05);

<Figure size 2160x2160 with 0 Axes>

From the violin plots above, we can conclude the following:¶

- Borrower APR decreases as the prosper score increases as expected. Borrower APR does not follow a specific trend with increasing loan term but it gets less variable as the term of the loan increases, Borrower APR decreases as the employment status improves from not employed to full-time employed and finally, borrower APR decreases as the monthly income range increases. Income range of 100,00 plus has the lowest APR whereas the not employed group has the highest APR. One interesting observation is the median borrower APR and IQR of the full-time employment looks to be bigger than that of part-time employment group.¶

- The original loan amount increases and varies more as the prosper rating improves, also, increasing the term of the loan might be a result of higher loan amounts which is expected. The interesting observation is that the employed category have the highest original loan amounts followed by the self-employed, the full-time employed and the not-employed group. The part-time employed look to have the lowest amount of loans. The 100k (USD) plus income range group has the biggest loans followed by 75k-100k (USD) and 50k-75k (USD).¶

Multivariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will create plots of three or more variables to investigate the data even further.

In [386]:
g = sb.FacetGrid(data = loans_sample, hue = 'IncomeRange', hue_order = ['$0', '$1-24,999', '$25,000-49,999','$50,000-74,999','$75,000-99,999','$100,000+','Not displayed'], size = 5, aspect = 1.5, palette = 'Spectral');
g.map(sb.regplot,"LoanOriginalAmount", "BorrowerAPR", fit_reg = True, scatter_kws = {'alpha':.5});
plt.legend(title = 'Income Ranges', loc = 'best', fontsize = 10);
plt.xscale('log');
plt.xlim(900, 40000);
plt.ylim(.05, .35);
g.fig.suptitle('Scatter Plot of APR vs. Original Loan Amount along Income Ranges', fontsize=14, y=1.05);

At first look, the APR does not look to be following a specific trend against the income ranges based on the regression lines. If we look closer, there is a negative relationship between APR and income range for the majority of income ranges, however, since there are very few data points that belong to the 0 dollar income it looks like the trend doesn't exist. If we ignore the red line (0 income), we can claim that the higher the income gets, the lower is the APR overal. There might be other factors like the Prosper score and the overal risk profile of the borrower that might play into this relationship.¶

We can see in the above scatter plot that the highest APR belongs to the not employed and the lowest APR belongs to the retired group, however, because of the limited number of data belonging to these 2 groups as well as the part-time group, we can not make claim that the relationship is statistically significant. When comparing the employed, full-time and the self-employed, it looks like the full-time and self-employed enjoy a lower APR than the employed group. These relationships might be influenced further by the income range and the borrower's overal financial risk. Similar to what we observed in the charts above, the part-time group's APR increases with increasing original loan amount.¶
